---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import PageHeader from '../components/sections/PageHeader.astro'
import Prose from '../components/ui/Prose.astro'
import FaqAccordion from '../components/ui/FaqAccordion.astro'
import { howToJsonLd, faqPageJsonLd, breadcrumbJsonLd } from '../lib/seo'

const path = '/ed25519-ssh-key'
const title = 'Ed25519 SSH keys: generate with ssh-keygen'
const description =
	'How to generate an Ed25519 SSH key with ssh-keygen, add it to GitHub or a server, and why Ed25519 beats RSA for SSH. Copy-paste commands and FAQ.'

const steps = [
	{
		name: 'Run ssh-keygen',
		text: 'In a terminal, run: ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com". The -t flag selects the Ed25519 key type and -C adds a label comment.',
	},
	{
		name: 'Choose where to save it',
		text: 'Press Enter to accept the default path ~/.ssh/id_ed25519. This writes the private key to id_ed25519 and the public key to id_ed25519.pub.',
	},
	{
		name: 'Set a passphrase',
		text: 'Type a strong passphrase when prompted. It encrypts the private key on disk so a stolen file cannot be used directly.',
	},
	{
		name: 'Add the key to ssh-agent',
		text: 'Start the agent with eval "$(ssh-agent -s)" and load the key with ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 so you are not prompted every time.',
	},
	{
		name: 'Install the public key',
		text: 'Copy the contents of ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub and add it to GitHub (Settings → SSH and GPG keys) or a server with ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub user@host.',
	},
]

const faqs = [
	{
		q: 'What is an Ed25519 SSH key?',
		a: 'An Ed25519 SSH key is an SSH key pair that uses the Ed25519 signature scheme (EdDSA on Curve25519) instead of RSA or ECDSA. The private key authenticates you to a server; the matching public key is installed on that server. Ed25519 keys are small (a 256-bit private key) and fast to verify.',
	},
	{
		q: 'How do I generate an Ed25519 SSH key?',
		a: 'Run ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com", accept the default file location, and set a passphrase. This creates ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 (private) and ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub (public).',
	},
	{
		q: 'Can Ed25519 be used for SSH?',
		a: 'Yes. OpenSSH has supported Ed25519 keys since version 6.5 (2014), and every current SSH client and server supports them. GitHub, GitLab, and major cloud providers all accept Ed25519 public keys.',
	},
	{
		q: 'Is Ed25519 better than RSA for SSH?',
		a: 'For new keys, yes. Ed25519 is faster, has a much smaller key and signature, and avoids the weak-randomness pitfalls of ECDSA. Keep an RSA key (3072 bits or more) only if you must connect to an old server that predates Ed25519 support.',
	},
	{
		q: 'Is Ed25519 the default key type in ssh-keygen?',
		a: 'Yes, since OpenSSH 9.5 (October 2023) ssh-keygen generates Ed25519 keys by default. On older OpenSSH versions the default is RSA, so pass -t ed25519 explicitly to be sure.',
	},
	{
		q: 'Why are Ed25519 SSH keys so short?',
		a: 'Elliptic-curve keys reach the same security as a much larger RSA key. An Ed25519 private key is a fixed 256 bits, so the -b (bit length) flag is ignored, and the public key in id_ed25519.pub is a single short line.',
	},
	{
		q: 'Where is the Ed25519 SSH key stored?',
		a: 'By default in your ~/.ssh directory: the private key is id_ed25519 and the public key is id_ed25519.pub. Keep the private file secret (permissions 600); the .pub file is safe to share.',
	},
]

const jsonLd = [
	howToJsonLd({
		name: 'How to generate an Ed25519 SSH key with ssh-keygen',
		description,
		steps,
	}),
	faqPageJsonLd(faqs),
	breadcrumbJsonLd([
		{ name: 'Home', path: '/' },
		{ name: 'Ed25519 SSH key', path },
	]),
]
---

<BaseLayout
	title={title}
	description={description}
	path={path}
	ogImage="/og/ed25519-ssh-key.png"
	jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
	<PageHeader
		title="Ed25519 SSH keys"
		lead="How to generate an Ed25519 SSH key with ssh-keygen, load it into ssh-agent, and add it to GitHub or a server — plus how Ed25519 compares to RSA for SSH."
		width="wide"
		illustration="private"
	/>

	<article class="px-4 pb-12 sm:px-6">
		<div class="mx-auto max-w-[1200px]">
			<Prose>
				<p>
					<strong>To generate an Ed25519 SSH key, run</strong>
					<code
						>ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"</code
					>, accept the default file location, and set a passphrase.
					That creates a private key at <code>~/.ssh/id_ed25519</code> and
					a public key at <code>~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub</code>. Add the
					public key to GitHub or your server and you are done. The
					rest of this guide explains each step, plus why Ed25519 is
					the recommended SSH key type today.
				</p>

				<h2>Generate an Ed25519 SSH key</h2>
				<p>Open a terminal and run:</p>
				<pre><code>ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"</code></pre>
				<p>
					<code>-t ed25519</code> selects the Ed25519 key type;
					<code>-C</code> adds a comment (an email or machine name) so you
					can tell keys apart later. <code>ssh-keygen</code> then asks two
					questions:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<strong>File location.</strong> Press Enter to accept the
						default, <code>~/.ssh/id_ed25519</code>. Choose a
						different name (for example <code
							>~/.ssh/id_ed25519_github</code
						>) if you keep a separate key per service.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Passphrase.</strong> Type a strong passphrase. It
						encrypts the private key on disk, so a copied
						<code>id_ed25519</code> file is useless without it. You can
						leave it empty for automation, but a passphrase plus
						<code>ssh-agent</code> is the safer default.
					</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					You now have two files: the private key
					<code>id_ed25519</code> (keep it secret) and the public key
					<code>id_ed25519.pub</code> (safe to share). For a deeper look
					at these two files, see
					<a href="/blog/id_ed25519/">what id_ed25519 is</a>.
				</p>

				<h3>Optional: harder-to-crack passphrase storage</h3>
				<p>
					Add <code>-a 100</code> to raise the number of key-derivation
					rounds, which makes a brute-force attack on the passphrase slower:
				</p>
				<pre><code>ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -a 100 -C "your_email@example.com"</code></pre>
				<p>
					Note that <code>-b</code> (bit length) has no effect on Ed25519:
					the key is always 256 bits. That is why these keys are so short
					compared to RSA.
				</p>

				<h2>Load the key into ssh-agent</h2>
				<p>
					So you only type your passphrase once per session, start the
					agent and add the key:
				</p>
				<pre><code>eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519</code></pre>
				<p>
					On macOS, <code
						>ssh-add --apple-use-keychain ~/.ssh/id_ed25519</code
					>
					also stores the passphrase in the Keychain.
				</p>

				<h2>Add the public key to GitHub or a server</h2>
				<p>Print the public key and copy the whole line:</p>
				<pre><code>cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub</code></pre>
				<p>It looks like this (one line):</p>
				<pre><code>ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAA... your_email@example.com</code></pre>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<strong>GitHub / GitLab:</strong> paste it into Settings →
						SSH and GPG keys → New SSH key.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>A server:</strong> install it in one command with
						<code>ssh-copy-id</code>:
					</li>
				</ul>
				<pre><code>ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub user@host</code></pre>
				<p>
					Test the connection with <code>ssh -T git@github.com</code> or
					<code>ssh user@host</code>. The first time you connect you
					will be asked to confirm the server's host key — if that
					server is GitHub, check the value against
					<a href="/blog/github-ssh-host-key-fingerprint-ed25519/"
						>GitHub's Ed25519 host key fingerprint</a
					>.
				</p>

				<h2>Ed25519 vs RSA for SSH</h2>
				<p>
					Ed25519 is the recommended default for new SSH keys. It is
					faster, far smaller, and harder to misuse than the
					alternatives.
				</p>
				<table>
					<thead>
						<tr>
							<th></th>
							<th>Ed25519</th>
							<th>RSA</th>
						</tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr>
							<td>Private key size</td>
							<td>256 bits (fixed)</td>
							<td>3072–4096 bits</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Public key line</td>
							<td>~68 characters</td>
							<td>several hundred</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Speed</td>
							<td>Very fast</td>
							<td>Slower</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Compatibility</td>
							<td>OpenSSH 6.5+ (2014)</td>
							<td>Universal</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
				<p>
					Keep an RSA key (at least 3072 bits) only for legacy servers
					that predate Ed25519. For a full breakdown, read
					<a href="/blog/ed25519-vs-rsa/">Ed25519 vs RSA</a>.
				</p>

				<h2>Is Ed25519 the default in ssh-keygen?</h2>
				<p>
					Since <strong>OpenSSH 9.5 (October 2023)</strong>,
					<code>ssh-keygen</code> generates Ed25519 keys by default when
					you run it with no <code>-t</code> flag. OpenSSH first added Ed25519
					support back in version 6.5 (2014). On anything older than 9.5
					the default is still RSA, so it is good practice to pass <code
						>-t ed25519</code
					> explicitly.
				</p>

				<h2>Experiment with raw Ed25519 keys</h2>
				<p>
					SSH private keys should always be generated locally with
					<code>ssh-keygen</code> — never in a browser. But if you want
					to
					<em>understand</em> the raw Ed25519 keypair and signatures that
					sit underneath, you can generate and sign with one in our in-browser
					tool, where keys never leave your device.
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<a href="/ed25519-key-generator/"
							>Ed25519 key generator</a
						> — create a raw 32-byte keypair.
					</li>
					<li>
						<a href="/ed25519-sign-message/">Sign a message</a> and
						<a href="/ed25519-verify-signature/"
							>verify a signature</a
						>.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</Prose>

			<section class="mt-12">
				<h2 class="display-lg">FAQ</h2>
				<div class="mt-5"><FaqAccordion faqs={faqs} /></div>
			</section>
		</div>
	</article>
</BaseLayout>
